[Rabies is a sporadic, ongoing problem in Bolivia, with cases occurring in dogs and cattle, with spillover to humans. The bat involved in these cases is the vampire bat (_Desmodus rotundus_), which occurs throughout tropical and subtropical areas in the Americas. Interestingly, a recent study casts doubt on the effectiveness of vampire bat control to reduce rabies transmission. However, an aggressive vaccination campaign of bovine animals and dogs in the area is prudent. It would be wise to vaccinate equine animals as well, because vampire bats may feed on them, too.

Although the risk of acquiring rabies virus infection through the consumption of meat from infected animals is very low, it is never prudent to consume tissues from any animals that are ill or dead. Conceivably, there might be risk of rabies virus infection from brain tissue removed and handled without gloves from rabies virus infected cattle for human consumption ("sesos"), which is a common dish in many parts of Latin America.

An image of the vampire bat can be accessed at http://www.animalpicturesarchive.com/WebImg/335/1208760244-t.jpg.

Maps of Bolivia can be seen at http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/bolivia_admin_2006.jpg and http://healthmap.org/r/3Rnt. A Map showing the location of Arani province, Cochabamba department can be accessed at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arani_Province. - Mod.TY]
